revision.text:
'''9 North''', or '''Nine North''', is a region of [[hydrothermal vents]] on the [[East Pacific Rise]] in the [[Pacific Ocean]], 900&nbsp;kilometers off the coast of [[Acapulco, Mexico]]; it has been so named by scientists because its latitude is 9°50'&nbsp;N.<ref name=Qiu>{{cite journal|last1=Qiu|first1=Jane|title=Oceanography: Death and rebirth in the deep|journal=Nature|date=20 May 2010|volume=465|issue=7296|pages=284–286|doi=10.1038/465284a|pmid=20485410}}</ref> It was first seen to erupt in 1991 by the [[DSV Alvin|deep submersible ''Alvin'']] during a survey for the [[Ocean Drilling Program]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lutz|first1=Richard|last2=Shank|first2=Timothy|last3=Evans|first3=Robert|title=Life After Death in the Deep Sea|journal=American Scientist|volume=89|issue=5|pages=422|doi=10.1511/2001.5.422|bibcode=2001AmSci..89..422L}}</ref> In November 1999, scientists, students, education specialists, and [[film crew]]s returned to 9 North to see how the biology and landscape had changed over time. IMAX, National Geographic, and BBC film crews have made videos about the [[hydrothermal vent|vent]]s at 9 North, most noticeably ''[[Volcanoes of the Deep Sea]]''.<ref name=MATE>{{cite web|title=9 Degrees North|url=http://archives.marinetech.org/nine_degrees/|publisher=Marine Advanced Technology Education Center|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>

BBC ''[[Planet Earth (2006 TV series)|Planet Earth]]'' series from 2006 reported that 9 North either extinguished or became inactive during the period that BBC was creating the series. All previously extant forms of life- crustaceans (shrimps, crabs) and tube worms- were observed to have disappeared (either died, or left the site), perhaps signalling the extinction of lifeforms unique to these particular vents.

