'''Amalur''' (sometimes '''Ama Lur''' or '''Ama Lurra'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aunamendi.eusko-ikaskuntza.eus/artikuluak/artikulua.php?id=eu&ar=96329|title=Mitologia - Auñamendi Eusko Entziklopedia|website=aunamendi.eusko-ikaskuntza.eus|language=eu|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref>) was the [[goddess]] of the [[earth]] in the religion of the ancient [[Basque people]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.es/books?id=UJc5BQ0G10YC&pg=PA85&dq=amalur&hl=es&sa=X&ei=eYzYT6vcG8eZ8QOFipH6Ag#v=onepage&q=amalur&f=false|title=Antropología simbólica vasca|last=Ortiz-Osés|first=Andrés|date=1985|publisher=Anthropos Editorial|isbn=9788485887842|language=es}}</ref> She was the mother of [[Ekhi]], the sun, and [[Ilazki]], the moon. Her name means "mother earth" or "mother land"; the 1968 [[Basque language|Basque]] documentary ''[[Ama lur]]'' was a celebration of the Basque countryside.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=YbEgCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA62&dq=%22amalur%22+basque&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiBnsnQvffdAhVVKH0KHewWCQAQ6AEILjAB#v=onepage&q=%22amalur%22%20basque&f=false|title=Spanish Spaces: Landscape, Space and Place in Contemporary Spanish Culture|last=Davies|first=Ann|date=2012-04-13|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9781781387962|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Patxi Xabier Lezama Perier |title=Basque Mythology: History of the myths and deities of the Basque Mythology |date=2018 |location=Euskadi Public Reading Network / Google |url=https://play.google.com/store/books/details/Basque_Mythology_History_of_the_myths_and_deities_?id=vlpZDwAAQBAJ&hl=en_US }}</ref>

